    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-01-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-01-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="652"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d652">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Choate</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram in cipher—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Embassy of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-01-01">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 1, 1900</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[Mr. Choate states that the only information the foreign office has regarding the
                    seizure of the British vessel <hi rend="italic">Mashona</hi> is that the vessel
                    was arrested by H. M. S. <hi rend="italic">Partridge</hi> with 1,700 bags of
                    flour marked <pb facs="0637" n="539" xml:id="pg_539"/> “Z. A. R.” and was
                    brought into prize court for trading with the enemy. It is claimed by the owners
                    that the flour was not destined for the South African Republic]</p>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
